title: For Sale:  Innovative Omni 9 mm Llama
postcontent:
Model: Omni
Caliber: 9 mm
Condition: Excellent!
Design:   Very Innovative
 
This is a very unique and “Difficult To Find Pistol.” This was Llama’s attempt to break into the premium segment, and they did it with fervor. They also wanted to show the world they could innovate and build a very high end pistol with features that rivaled even the best.  They chose the gun to carry the popular 9 mm para (9x19) cartridge.
The Omni was the most original and sophisticated Llama ever designed, incorporating very innovative and unique (and costly) features such as:
 Micro ball bearings for the hammer pivot create an exceptionally smooth action and very long-wearing durability.
 Separate draw bars for the single and double action sears.
 A deeply undercut trigger guard to allow high hand positioning for recoil control.
 "Buttressed" rifling, which used a 2-stage "step-down" from the lands to the grooves, for less bullet deformation and a better gas seal.
 An almost space age design and appearance.
 Solid steel frame.
 
These features and construction impart excellent reliability and smooth functioning. The solid ball bearing pivot, separate single/double action sear draw bars produce an exceptionally smooth, controlled shooting experience. The solid steel frame takes up a lot of the recoil, further enhancing the shooter’s feeling of stability and control.
Most of these features have never been found all together in any other single design, and they provide this pistol with an extremely smooth and reliable action.  Shooters who have the gun praise it as an excellent weapon.
As a result of all these high end features, the Omni production costs were very high (much higher than other guns they produced) and it was difficult to compete with more established rivals.  The Omni could not command the price or attention away from the top end gun manufacturers, and Llama has since shied away from trying to compete nose-to-nose with premium brands.
** Their loss is your gain in the form of the feature-rich Omni!   The list price of the Omni 9mm in the 1983 Gun Digest was $599.99,
Includes high capacity magazine.
 
* No trades. No silly low offers -- these messages will not be returned.
  This item is for sale.  It is not necessary to ask if it is still available.  If you are reading the ad, it is available.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer Ultra Compact Carry 9 mm
postcontent:
Brand: Sig Saurer
Caliber: 9 mm (9x19)
 
This is Sig’s smallest 9mm – excellent for concealed carry, the P290RS. Includes factory carry case and factory magazine with pinky extension.
Gun is built with all the quality and workmanship that Sig Sauer is famous for.
The trigger mechanism is the defining feature on the P290 RS. The suffix in its designation stands for Re-Strike. . The trigger gives an immediate second “shot” at a recalcitrant primer in the event of a misfire. Some don’t see this as a big deal, because they follow the doctrine that a bad round that’s failed them once doesn’t get a second chance, and their preferred response to a “click” instead of a “bang” is a fast “tap-rack-assess the situation in front of you.”
Friendly for dry fire. Instead of having to interrupt your trigger pulling practice by breaking your hold and retracting the slide between dry “shots,” the P290RS owner can roll the trigger continuously.
Following Sig's allegiance to craftmanship and quality, both front and rear sights are MILLED and DOVETAILED into the steel of slide for durability and easily visible.
Subtle, rounded beavertail at the rear of the grip tang that accommodates smaller-handed shooters and those with meatier paws, where it could be a deal-breaker for other little 9mm guns.
The lower rear edge on the slide-lock lever of the earlier P290 had a rather sharp corner, and I can see where that would have been a problem for those who shoot with straight thumbs. That corner has been very nicely rounded slide-lock lever feels great any way you hold gun, including those who shoot with straight thumbs (something other manufacturers ignore on powerful subcompact pistols).
Big, easy to find magazine relearse button is easy to find and press, especially when you are in a hurry. Mag release button has just the right height above the frame: not too low that you can’t find it and not too high where you accidently pop the mag.
Rounded slide stop is easy to use and comfortable to feel.  No sharp uncomfortable edges – incorporates all the Sig workmanship and attention to detail that you’d expect.
The perfect trigger pull you expect from Sig Sauer. Comfort is exquisite: no sharp edges anywhere.
Ergonomics are brilliant: Sig really paid a lot of attention to ergonomics (included the smartly rounded, smooth edges all over), especially in this gun where the compact frame makes shooters more sensitive to good design. But it works well and feels comfortable for large and small hands. Easily concealable in jacket pocket or holster. Also, you can put your thumb on the flat hammer and holster the P290RS without fear of an unintended discharge if a drawstring from a warm-up jacket or something like that got fouled in the trigger area.
This handy little 20.5-ounce seven-shooter is a definite contender in the currently hot niche of subcompact 9mm carry pistols.
* No trades. No silly low offers -- these messages will not be returned.
  This item is for sale.  It is not necessary to ask if it is still available.  If you are reading the ad, it is available.
